Your service lives in its own repository, completely separate from the Trellis core. Create a standalone `orders-service` project in your language runtime:

<LanguageTabs>
{#snippet ts()}

Create a new Deno project:

```sh
mkdir orders-service && cd orders-service
deno init
```

Add the Trellis SDK and TypeBox, our schema library, as dependencies:

```sh
deno add npm:@qlever-llc/trellis npm:@sinclair/typebox
```

If you are using Node.js instead, use `npm`:

```sh
npm install @qlever-llc/trellis @sinclair/typebox
```

{/snippet}
{#snippet rust()}

Create a new Cargo binary project:

```sh
cargo new orders-service --bin
cd orders-service
mkdir contracts
```

Add the runtime, contract, and generated-SDK dependencies. Use the current Trellis release version for the Trellis crates:

```toml
[dependencies]
anyhow = "1"
async-nats = "0.41"
bytes = "1"
clap = { version = "4", features = ["derive", "env"] }
futures-util = "0.3"
serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
serde_json = "1"
time = { version = "0.3", features = ["formatting"] }
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["macros", "rt-multi-thread", "signal"] }
tracing = "0.1"
tracing-subscriber = { version = "0.3", features = ["env-filter"] }
ulid = "1.2"

trellis-contracts = "0.10"
trellis-rs = "0.10"

# Add this after the first prepare run creates the generated SDK crate.
trellis-sdk-orders-service = { path = "generated/packages/cargo/orders-service" }
```

In the Trellis monorepo, these dependencies are workspace dependencies instead of published versions. Standalone services should use the published crate versions or a `[patch]` that points at a local Trellis checkout during development.

{/snippet}
</LanguageTabs>
